 and building institutions in the hope of advancing civilization. Religion played a decisive role. Today, more evangelical Protestants live in Texas than in any other state. They have influenced every presidential election for fifty years, mobilized powerful efforts against abortion and same-sex marriage, and been a driving force in the Tea Party movement. And religion has always been complicated by race and ethnicity.Drawing from memoirs, newspapers, oral history, voting records, and surveys, Rough Country tells the stories of ordinary men and women who struggled with the conditions they faced, conformed to the customs they knew, and on occasion emerged as powerful national leaders. We see the lasting imprint of slavery, public executions, Jim Crow segregation, and resentment against the federal government. We also observe courageous efforts to care for the sick, combat lynching, provide for the poor, welcome new immigrants, and uphold liberty of conscience.A monumental and magisterial history, Rough Country is as much about the rest of America as it is about Texas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / Southwest (AZ, NM, OK, TX).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015z978311044418608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015z978311066592540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400852116zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400852116.jpg  a978-3-11-044418-6  PUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015  a978-3-11-066592-5  PUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-al